  CORE ARGUMENT: McElwee provides a taxonomic analysis of demandingness objections, distinguishing "cost-based" objections (morality requires too much sacrifice) from "directive force" objections (morality issues too many requirements). He argues that many alleged solutions to demandingness (like satisficing) only address one dimension while failing on the other. A successful response must explain both why certain costs are too demanding and why morality's directive authority has limits.

  RELEVANCE: McElwee's distinction between cost and directive force dimensions illuminates why simple percentage thresholds (like 10%) may not fully solve demandingness. Even if 10% isn't too costly for affluent agents, the continuous obligation to give may create excessive directive force - morality governing too much of life. This suggests that complete giving norms might need both quantitative thresholds (how much) and qualitative limits (when obligation applies).

  POSITION: Meta-level analysis of demandingness objections; argues for multidimensional understanding of what makes theories demanding.
