  RELEVANCE: York's modal approach has implications for evaluating giving norms: income-based thresholds like 10% may appear reasonable in affluent societies but extremely demanding (or insufficiently demanding) in radically different economic circumstances. This suggests that robust giving norms should be formulated with sensitivity to modal variation - perhaps asset-based norms better track what agents can sacrifice across varied economic conditions.

