  CORE ARGUMENT: Bradley argues that satisficing consequentialism - which permits agents to aim for "good enough" outcomes rather than optimal ones - faces fatal objections. Crucially, satisficing permits agents to prevent better outcomes from obtaining, which violates the core consequentialist commitment that better outcomes are always preferable. Any coherent satisficing view must explain why it's permissible to block improvements, but no such explanation is compatible with genuine consequentialism.

  RELEVANCE: Bradley's critique challenges attempts to justify fixed giving thresholds (like 10% of income) on satisficing grounds. If giving 15% would produce better outcomes than 10%, satisficing seems to permit arbitrarily stopping at 10%, which conflicts with consequentialist foundations. This suggests that defensible income-based thresholds must be grounded in something other than satisficing - perhaps Murphy's cooperative principle or Hooker's rule-consequentialism.

