  CORE ARGUMENT: Norcross defends "scalar consequentialism," which abandons deontic categories (right/wrong, obligatory/permissible) entirely in favor of purely scalar evaluation (better/worse). On this view, there are no obligations or permissions, only actions that produce more or less good. This dissolves the demandingness objection: there's nothing to be too demanding about if there are no demands, only a spectrum from better to worse actions.

  RELEVANCE: Scalar consequentialism radically reframes the question about giving norms: there's no threshold separating obligatory from supererogatory giving, just a continuum where more giving is always better. This challenges the very coherence of debates over whether 10% vs. 20% is "required" - all such questions dissolve into questions of degree. However, for practical purposes, scalar consequentialism provides no action-guidance on where to stop giving, which is precisely what giving pledges attempt to provide.

